WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
 >> Hello, and welcome to another walkthrough for Django for everybody.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:10.880
 A big part of the first half of this class is what I call the big picture.

00:00:10.880 --> 00:00:15.280
 So in the big picture, you are basically, we're trying to basically learn

00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:19.000
 the ways of a Python Django application.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:22.960
 A Django application, Django is an application

00:00:22.960 --> 00:00:27.760
 that then you create objects and load those objects in.

00:00:27.760 --> 00:00:33.240
 And in those objects, you achieve your web application.

00:00:33.240 --> 00:00:37.000
 And so this is the flow where the request-response cycle.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:38.960
 So we've got a browser on the left-hand side.

00:00:38.960 --> 00:00:42.120
 We've got the internet, very tiny in the middle.

00:00:42.120 --> 00:00:46.120
 And then we've got Django, which is running in a Linux server, and

00:00:46.120 --> 00:00:51.920
 a whole bunch of files that you either have or will be editing.

00:00:51.920 --> 00:00:56.320
 And the big flow is that the user requests a page in the browser,

00:00:56.320 --> 00:00:59.280
 which gets routed into your application.

00:00:59.280 --> 00:01:05.280
 And your application may read database data or whatever, produce some output,

00:01:05.280 --> 00:01:09.800
 and then send it back to the browser where the browser looks at the response and

00:01:09.800 --> 00:01:10.720
 shows it to the user.

00:01:10.720 --> 00:01:13.240
 The request-response cycle,

00:01:13.240 --> 00:01:18.320
 that is the essential engine of browsers and the internet.

00:01:18.320 --> 00:01:22.720
 Now, this picture may be the best way for you to think about it.

00:01:22.720 --> 00:01:27.320
 Or you may also just think about it as a set of folders and files.

00:01:27.320 --> 00:01:31.120
 Because really, when you're developing your application,

00:01:31.120 --> 00:01:33.200
 you're working with folders and files.

00:01:33.200 --> 00:01:36.560
 Now, the screenshot I'm showing you that has a folder autos, hello, home,

00:01:36.560 --> 00:01:40.920
 my site, polls, site, is not like at the very beginning.

00:01:40.920 --> 00:01:45.160
 At this point, it has several applications and several folders.

00:01:45.160 --> 00:01:48.760
 And it might be a little bit easier to understand the big picture when we think

00:01:48.760 --> 00:01:52.240
 about it from a point of view of multiple applications.

00:01:52.240 --> 00:01:57.160
 So in this particular one, their site has files in it, home has files in it.

00:01:57.160 --> 00:02:02.320
 Hello is an application, autos is an application, and polls is an application.

00:02:02.320 --> 00:02:06.160
 You may have already done them, or they may be in the future.

00:02:06.160 --> 00:02:08.640
 Ultimately, in comes a request.

00:02:08.640 --> 00:02:15.640
 And there are parts of your application that participate in that request.

00:02:15.640 --> 00:02:20.400
 So when your application is starting, so if your application doesn't start up very

00:02:20.400 --> 00:02:24.720
 well, or it blows up, or it shows the something went wrong message.

00:02:24.720 --> 00:02:28.480
 That probably means, as it was reading settings.py and then the rest of these

00:02:28.480 --> 00:02:32.040
 files, there was something wrong with the file, then you gotta go fix the files.

00:02:32.040 --> 00:02:36.560
 But let's assume that things in settings.py and the rest of the files,

00:02:36.560 --> 00:02:40.920
 at least, are syntactically correct enough so that the application loads.

00:02:40.920 --> 00:02:45.320
 Well, Django is a Python application that, in a sense,

00:02:45.320 --> 00:02:48.720
 is listening for incoming requests.

00:02:48.720 --> 00:02:53.360
 And those requests come to Django, but then once it gets a request,

00:02:53.360 --> 00:03:00.360
 like a URL, like /polls or /polls/2 for a detail page.

00:03:00.360 --> 00:03:04.760
 It looks at urls.py, and that's the one that's in mysiteurls.py.

00:03:04.760 --> 00:03:10.840
 So there's two urls.py, there's the pollsurls.py, and that's the second one.

00:03:10.840 --> 00:03:14.200
 And then there's mysiteurls.py.

00:03:14.200 --> 00:03:18.520
 In the mysite folder, you can see that there is settings.py,

00:03:18.520 --> 00:03:22.160
 which says here is how I'm going to set up my Django environment, and

00:03:22.160 --> 00:03:25.320
 also all the applications that I want to load.

00:03:25.320 --> 00:03:29.920
 And then for each of the applications, you're going to see a urls.py and

00:03:29.920 --> 00:03:34.520
 a views.py, and perhaps, as we get more advanced, the forms,

00:03:34.520 --> 00:03:38.880
 models, and then even admin.py for each application.

00:03:38.880 --> 00:03:42.280
 So other than the mysiteurls.py,

00:03:42.280 --> 00:03:47.520
 the rest of it is kind of replicated as often as you want.

00:03:47.520 --> 00:03:55.280
 So let's take a look at some sample code in Python Anywhere.

00:03:55.280 --> 00:04:00.160
 So here we go, I've got my home directory, Django projects, mysite.

00:04:00.160 --> 00:04:03.920
 Now, one of the things that's a little bit tricky to figure out is,

00:04:03.920 --> 00:04:10.140
 mysite is the overall configuration for the entire Django project.

00:04:10.140 --> 00:04:15.080
 autos is an application, hello is an application, and polls is an application.

00:04:15.080 --> 00:04:19.440
 But mysite is the configuration for the project.

00:04:19.440 --> 00:04:25.000
 But really this actually starts, the first thing to start your application

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:30.360
 is the settings.py, and this is all of your configuration,

00:04:30.360 --> 00:04:35.480
 what applications, polls, home, and autos are the three applications

00:04:35.480 --> 00:04:40.000
 that I'm going to be loading here, but it really starts before this.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:50.000
 [MUSIC]

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:56.040
 So if I go to the web setup, this is the configuration for

00:04:56.040 --> 00:04:59.000
 djfree.pythonanywhere.com.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:02.760
 So if I go to djfree.pythonanywhere.com,

00:05:02.760 --> 00:05:08.720
 that routes to my application running in Python Anywhere.

00:05:08.720 --> 00:05:11.320
 So djfree.pythonanywhere.com.

00:05:11.320 --> 00:05:19.500
 And so this somehow has got a domain name, and it routes into a Linux system,

00:05:19.500 --> 00:05:24.000
 but then it eventually starts your application and routes to your application.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:28.080
 So from here on down, if you put something on there,

00:05:28.080 --> 00:05:32.640
 you don't really have to worry too much about the first part,

00:05:32.640 --> 00:05:36.480
 djfree.pythonanywhere.com, but you do have to worry about what you're going to,

00:05:36.480 --> 00:05:40.960
 how you're going to handle, and how you're going to write the rest of this URL, right?

00:05:40.960 --> 00:05:44.520
 So I just put in a bad one, and we get page not found.

00:05:44.520 --> 00:05:47.480
 And that's not like your application is running.

00:05:47.480 --> 00:05:52.120
 You requested a page that your application does not know how to respond to, okay?

00:05:52.120 --> 00:05:59.440
 Now, if you have problems, you got to make sure that your source code and

00:05:59.440 --> 00:06:02.520
 your working directory are your home directory.

00:06:02.520 --> 00:06:07.760
 And then you want to make sure that this wiskey.py is properly set up.

00:06:07.760 --> 00:06:10.520
 But that was set up in the very first assignment, and

00:06:10.520 --> 00:06:12.280
 you shouldn't need to change that.

00:06:12.280 --> 00:06:15.480
 You got to have your virtual environment correctly set.

00:06:15.480 --> 00:06:18.160
 You got to have your Python version correctly set.

00:06:18.160 --> 00:06:22.480
 And if you have problems, you can look at the server log and the error log.

00:06:22.480 --> 00:06:24.960
 If you're really having terrible problems debugging things.

00:06:24.960 --> 00:06:27.320
 But we're not going to talk so much about debugging.

00:06:27.320 --> 00:06:30.320
 We're going to talk today about routing.

00:06:30.320 --> 00:06:36.200
 Python Anywhere starts when you hit the reload button, it reads settings.py.

00:06:36.200 --> 00:06:39.560
 The wiskey config tells it to read settings.py.

00:06:39.560 --> 00:06:43.640
 And then all the rest of setup of your particular Django instance

00:06:43.640 --> 00:06:47.480
 depends on what you tell it in settings.py.

00:06:47.480 --> 00:06:51.720
 So let's take a look at the settings.py because it's the beginning of your

00:06:51.720 --> 00:06:53.080
 application.

00:06:53.080 --> 00:06:54.680
 So there's a few things.

00:06:54.680 --> 00:06:58.720
 Now, one of the things is this allowed host, which in an early assignment,

00:06:58.720 --> 00:07:01.720
 I set it up so that I told you to say anywhere.

00:07:01.720 --> 00:07:05.720
 And that has to do with the fact that there is some filtering going on about

00:07:05.720 --> 00:07:11.040
 whether or not it actually is going to accept any requests from the internet to

00:07:11.040 --> 00:07:11.800
 your application.

00:07:11.800 --> 00:07:14.560
 So you can put a filter in a sense.

00:07:14.560 --> 00:07:19.520
 So we're saying with the settings allowed host equals star,

00:07:19.520 --> 00:07:22.120
 we're saying don't put a filter in.

